node.text:
Watch this short video by @kabuki_virtualcoaching coaches @bmorg33 and @colbs_cass_lifts to learn more on why lumbar extension can lead to many issues and is not optimal for movement under load. We first need to understand WHY it is happening. The two most common reasons it tends to happen are:

▪️Chest up leading to poor hinge mechanics. We need to let ones chest hinge forward.

▪️Poor breathing patterns leading to a lack of IAP being built and spine stability jeopardized.

Once we understand why it is happening we can make strides to fix it thus decreasing injury risk and improving our ability to handle load.
 
Make sure to follow @kabuki_virtualcoaching for more educational videos like this one. 
 
THIS WEEKEND -> Join us for a live virtual Principles of Loaded Movement course and develop movement mastery through a 2-day, 16hr intensive lecture course. Recordings included so you can watch at your convenience if you can’t make the live event. Link in story.

node.title: Tag Someone Whose Squat Looks Like This: Lumbar Extension

If you are not familiar with Kabuki barbells and why tens of thousands of lifters, coaches, athletes, and clinicians use and endorse them, check out this great video by @kabuki_virtualcoaching coaches @brandon_senn and @colbs_cass_lifts that goes over some of the advantages of training with purpose-built, biomechanically-sound barbells like the Duffalo Bar and Transformer Bar.
-
A standard 45lb barbell is one of the most common implements in the weight room and it's also one of the least forgiving. In our experience we see training related pain and injuries occurring more frequently when people force themselves into positions that they don't have the mobility for or proper joint stability. Using specialty bars can be one tool to help you train harder and in better positions.

Learn the Bird Dog as presented by @kabuki_virtualcoaching coaches @brandon_senn and @colbs_cass_lifts
-
The bird dog exercise is one of the most common exercises prescribed by rehab pros for low back pain and dysfunction. Even if you aren't in pain its a fantastic drill to learn how to move your hips and shoulders off of a stable core. It can improve your shoulder stability for overhead pressing and even your hinge mechanics in a squat and deadlift. However, due to its popularity, it tends to be an exercise that is performed incorrectly more often than not. If you can master the positions of the bird dog you will undoubtedly get stronger faster by virtue of improved biomechanics.
——

node.text:
Our @kabuki_virtualcoaching team films and produces FREE high quality educational content like this every day for the community. If you follow our brand, you are missing out big time if you don’t also follow @kabuki_virtualcoaching. Check out some of the latest videos they’ve posted and drop suggestions or video requests in the comments below.
-
Building an effective arch for bench pressing is not just for powerlifters. Global tension is important for maximizing energy transfer and establishing a good base for your shoulder girdle to work from. Global tension does not mean reducing the range of motion thought that could be a goal of most bench pressers.

Global tension allows the entire spine to be equally loaded which reduces the acute loading at the lumbar spine.

Video Highlights:

- Focus on uprighting and extending your upper back first and letting your lower back arch to the amount necessary

- Unless you only want to improve your bench press dont focus on reducing your range if motion. Exercises that have a high mechanic tension tension and large ROM are the bread and butter of hypertrophy training. Reducing the ROM only means less muscle mass gain in most situations.

node.text:
A few weeks back we released a free resource for those who wish to DIY their own rack! Link in story, and make sure to check our free DIY Barbell plan as well!
•••
#repost @mad_scientist_duffin
-
This may be controversial to say as an equipment supplier, but yes, a well-made DIY Wood Rack can be both viable and safe. At @kabukistrength we would rather see people lifting than not.
-
Many folks as of late have been unable to access equipment or are on limited budgets, but that shouldn’t keep you from training. I grew up homeless and living in wilderness shacks (see last post), and I still found a way to train and get the work in. I love seeing the ingenuity of simply getting it done so you can train, and was inspired to see what I could put together for a small budget.
-
As an engineer and equipment manufacturer, I want to take a stance and say that this is viable option, provide you some inspiration for ideas, and even some prints our design engineer put together for your DIY project. In all honesty, these are better alternatives than a cheap-o rack from Amazon or Walmart.  This is also a great way to keep training while saving up for a better rack. I built this one for less than $75 and in under 1 hour!
-
Swipe up on my story or head over to www.kabukistrength.com/DIY and we’ll email you a PDF containing technical drawings and a materials list you can get started with. Have fun and build safe!
-
PS. Watch ‘till the end to see me take my creation for a ride with some heavy squats!
-

node.text:
With a rapidly changing fitness landscape, barbells are seemingly harder and harder to come by. Our engineering manager Adam has come up with a simple, affordable DIY solution for making your own barbell using materials you can buy locally and/or online. We believe strength training and fitness should be accessible to anyone, and this is our initiative to provide free, high quality DIY plans and ideas to the community. #KabukiDIY #DIYBarbell
-
Depending on how savvy of a shopper you are, you can build this bar for between $50-$75, maybe even less. Watch this video to learn more + swipe up on our story or visit kabukistrength.com/DIY to download the PDF with technical drawings, material list, sourcing info, and more instruction.
-
Have any requests or ideas for what you would like to see DIY plans for next? Drop them in the comments below!
-

#kabukistrength #kabukiculture

Very cool FREE training resources from our coaching staff @kabuki_virtualcoaching. Watch this short video with our head coach @brandon_senn explaining the starter template concept, then swipe up on our story to get access! AVAILABLE UNTIL SUNDAY MIDNIGHT PST.

Designed to bring you up to a point of high trainability while rapidly improving strength, this template is perfect for anyone who is returning to the gym after a short layoff or an individual who wants to experience Kabuki Strength program design for a fresh start. Starter Templates give you an effective point to begin a new program while providing instructions for progression as if you we're working with one of our Coaches 1-on-1.
-
Sign up and you'll get access to a private page where you can download the FORGE template, watch an instructional video on use and progression, and ask our coaches questions!
-
Starter Templates are 100% FREE but only available for download the first week they are launched. After the first week it will be gone forever. FORGE template access expires next Sunday, June 14 at midnight.

node.text:
Today's guest is the legendary @tmacsinc, a retired SpecOps operator who is now one of the top instructors in tactical training, marksmanship, and performance-based physical training for the tactically-minded through his company @combatstrengthtraining. 
Our hosts and Pat discuss general preparedness, fitness, proficiency, and the differences in preparing for dynamic, multi-plane human function as is necessary in a tactical environment. Pat draws from his experiences as a member of 1st SFOD-D (Delta Force) in hostile areas to work with individuals in a variety of skillsets outside of just marksmanship. He talks us through his combat strength training program and the kind of training methodologies and philosophies they draw from.

Thanks for joining us on Strength Chat @tmacsinc
PODCAST SIGNATURE •
Hope you enjoy! As always, please leave us a review and tell all your friends about Strength Chat 🙂
•••••
Hosted by the Mad Scientist of Strength, Dr. Rudolph, and The Wizard of Training. @mad_scientist_duffin @rudykadlub @brandon_senn
•••••
Available on iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, IGTV, Google Play, and Stitcher as well! Make sure to subscribe!

node.text:
How do you approach technique work? Is it based on a perception of what a squat “should look like” or is it grounded in sound biomechanical principles about how the body functions?
-
We find that people start at the wrong place when they want to improve their technique. Following a process is the best way to improve almost every component of training and improving your technique is no different.
-
Positions > Drills > Soft Tissue Work
-
DID YOU KNOW that Kabuki Strength has a full-time staff of coaches working at the Lab who produce educational content like the video above, teach continuing ed. courses all over the world, and work with hundreds of strength athletes to help them reach their goals?
-
In fact, we consider ourselves an education company first - a characteristic that bleeds into every aspect of our organization - from the equipment we manufacture, the content we produce, and the incredible folks we work with. Here is a fantastic example of the kind of content you will find for free, posted daily, on our @kabuki_virtualcoaching page.
-
If you’d like to learn more about our education and coaching services or talk to a coach via a free strategy call, hit the link in our story!
-

We couldn’t have explained any better ourselves why #kabuknurl is the best bar knurling in the iron game. Don’t believe us, talk to someone who has held a NewGen Squat or Power Bar! The bar-to-human interface is knurl, and it is of vital importance to performance, durability, and function. Love the review guys @samdabeast_ @beast_barbell, and for anyone who wants to watch these gentlemen smash serious weights hit the link in our story for the full video.

The Transformer continues to hold its place as one of the most revolutionary speciality bars on the market. Make squatting in good position easier and keep your shoulders and elbows healthy with the Transformer’s unique design. Better squats, stronger athletes—swipe up in today’s story to learn more about this outstanding addition to any gym space. ⁣

node.text:
Lifting weights isn’t much of a team sport, but life finds a way and nothing is going to stop Coach Kyle And Coach Brandon from hitting single-arm swings together with the ShouldeRök. ⁣
⁣
The ShouldeRök is an incredibly versatile piece of equipment that can be utilized to increase shoulder mobility as well as strengthen the shoulder. Speaking of partner work—the ShouldeRök’s unique length and shape makes it a perfect tool for performing tissue work on a training partner. ⁣
⁣
Swipe up in today’s story to learn more about what the ShouldeRök can do for you—alone or with a friend.⁣
⁣
⁣

Our bars are have been crazy great from the very beginning, and in the beginning our bar testing sometimes got a little crazy. Here’s to the time we loaded a Duffalo bar prototype with over 700 pounds and our fearless Creative Director extraordinaire @andreimiclea risked it all for the gram. Kabuki Strength and its testing methods have come a long way from 2014, and we’re proud to say that only one 2.5 pound plate was harmed in the making of this film.⁣
⁣

The Duffalo Bar has been a part of preparation for many incredible athletic performances, and Kabuki Customer Service head @charlietuna6’s recent accomplishments at USPA Drug-Tested Nationals added another strong bullet point to this bar's resume. Shown here using the Duffalo for some pressing work going into this meet, Charlie went on to destroy her own world record bench of 253.5 lbs from the year before with a new open world record of 264.5 lbs at age 50.⁣
⁣
We are incredibly proud of our talented staff and honored to manufacture bars that support outstanding performances around the country and around the world. Swipe up in today's story and learn more about the Duffalo's joint-friendly engineering.⁣
⁣
Side note: this is one of Charlie's go-to hype songs, and it's almost as fierce as she is.⁣

node.text:
Kabuki co-founder and CEO @rudykadlub made some major moves at USPA Drug-Tested Nationals in Palm Springs, CA with this 1234.5 total in the 100 kg weight class. Rudy, who's 72 years young, nailed a 429.9 squat, a 303.1 bench, and a 501.5 deadlift and also hit a 308 lb bench in a fourth attempt. All these lifts are world records, and Rudy took home best lifter to top off this incredible work. Rudy spends the majority of his squat and bench training time using our specialty bars, with straight bar work only taking place during meet prep. And this song? It's fitting--and it's one of Rudy's training hype songs. Congratulations, Rudy--you earned every pound, and here's to many more in the future.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Follow @rudykadlub to keep up with his training strategy and progress towards his next meet!⁣⁣

node.text:
Hey folks, @mad_scientist_duffin here. I'm proud to announce the launch of a project I've been working on with my team at Kabuki Strength - The Kyūbell. 
-
Developed in partnership with @havakdesigns, the #Kyūbell is a variable load/vector handheld training device. The inspiration behind this device was to provide a tool that could offer versatility to commonly loaded exercises. The unique ability of the Kyūbell to target different segments of a force curve allows users make some exercises more or less challenging depending on the chosen position. 
Kyūbells are extremely well-rounded in their application for their size. Unlike a traditional dumbbell, the variable positions and grips on each Kyūbell mean a wider gamut of exercise selection and load compared to a single weight dumbbell. Kyūbells are an excellent choice for the space-conscious gym user who wants maximum versatility and training effect from his curated collection of strength equipment. Simple guides on each bell allow a new user to quickly understand the basic positions and grips through intuitive illustrations.
-
Pronounced like the letter "Q", the word Kyū is a term used to denote mastery of activities, grades or degrees of proficiency, in particular around reference to movement (historically in the martial arts). It is also a play on the number 9, integral to the design of this 3-handle bell. Kyū is a fitting root word for this unique piece of equipment.
-
Over the last year I’ve had an absolute blast developing and incorporating this concept through my own training as I transitioned from record-breaking #grandgoals lifts to my own flavor of sustainable-yet-challenging training at home and in the gym.
-
To learn more about the physics and reasoning behind the Kyūbell, check out the 15m whiteboard video I filmed (it's posted on the product page).
-
Appreciate you guys as always for supporting #kabukistrength
